    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You will need to use <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> or such.</p>\n\n<p><code>List&lt;String&gt;</code> is an interface.</p>\n\n<p>Use this:  </p>\n\n<pre><code>import java.util.ArrayList;\n\n...\n\nList&lt;String&gt; supplierNames = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 428088,
      "reputation" : 3181,
      "user_id" : 810176,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 85,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e9ff0141996fa23b6447209e3f60a193?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Ankit",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/810176/ankit"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 15,
    "last_activity_date" : 1352973736,
    "creation_date" : 1352973736,
    "answer_id" : 13395134,
    "question_id" : 13395114,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>List is an interface, and you can not initialize an interface. Instantiate an implementing class instead.</p>\n\n<p>Like:</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; abc = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\nList&lt;String&gt; xyz = new LinkedList&lt;String&gt;();\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1864884,
      "reputation" : 861,
      "user_id" : 1688697,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/Pypcy.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Doseke",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1688697/doseke"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 43,
    "last_activity_date" : 1484306735,
    "last_edit_date" : 1484306735,
    "creation_date" : 1352973763,
    "answer_id" : 13395145,
    "question_id" : 13395114,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>List is an <em>Interface</em>, you cannot instantiate an Interface, because interface is a convention, what methods should have your classes. In order to instantiate, you need some realizations(implementations) of that interface. Try the below code with very popular implementations of List interface:</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; supplierNames = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;(); \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>or</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; supplierNames = new LinkedList&lt;String&gt;();\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 293490,
      "reputation" : 574,
      "user_id" : 596808,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c4ebecdb8b2cc721b229cb260591c667?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Uli",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/596808/uli"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 7,
    "last_activity_date" : 1352973780,
    "creation_date" : 1352973780,
    "answer_id" : 13395149,
    "question_id" : 13395114,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Depending on what kind of List you want to use, something like</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; supplierNames = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>should get you going.</p>\n\n<p>List is the interface, ArrayList is one implementation of the List interface. More implementations that may better suit your needs can be found by reading the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/List.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">JavaDocs of the List interface</a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
